          "input": {
            "command": "cat >> /home/shako/REPOS/Indie-Hacking/deepagents/deepagents-cli-course.html << 'HTMLEOF'\n\n<!-- MODULE 5: Clever Tricks -->\n<section class=\"module\" id=\"module-5\">\n  <div class=\"module__inner\">\n\n    <div class=\"module__header animate-in\">\n      <div class=\"module__number\">Module 5</div>\n      <h1 class=\"module__title\">The Clever Tricks</h1>\n      <p class=\"module__subtitle\">Several smart patterns make this CLI feel polished: lazy loading, context summarization, unicode security, and a smart shell allow-list.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 1: Lazy loading -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Lazy loading — keeping startup fast</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">The CLI must launch quickly — even for a simple <code>deepagents --version</code>. Heavy imports (the AI SDK, LangChain, Textual) are deferred until they're actually needed.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"translation-block\">\n        <div class=\"translation-block__header\">config.py — bootstrap pattern</div>\n        <div class=\"translation-block__grid\">\n          <div class=\"translation-block__code\">\n<pre class=\"code-pre\"><div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">1</span><span>def _ensure_bootstrap() -> None:</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">2</span><span>    global _bootstrap_done</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">3</span><span>    if _bootstrap_done: return</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">4</span><span>    with _bootstrap_lock:</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">5</span><span>        if _bootstrap_done: return  # double-check</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">6</span><span>        _load_dotenv()             # read .env file</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">7</span><span>        _override_langsmith_project()</div>\n<div class=\"code-line\"><span class=\"code-line__num\">8</span><span>        _bootstrap_done = True</div></pre>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"translation-block__english\">\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 3</strong> — If bootstrap already ran, exit immediately. No work needed.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 4</strong> — <strong>Thread lock</strong>: prevents two threads from running bootstrap simultaneously (important in a Textual app where background workers may start concurrently).</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 5</strong> — <strong>Double-checked locking</strong>: after acquiring the lock, check again. The first thread sets the flag; subsequent threads skip everything.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 6</strong> — Read the <code>.env</code> file from the project root (or cwd) to load API keys and config.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 7</strong> — Override the <code>LANGSMITH_PROJECT</code> env var so agent traces go to a separate LangSmith project from the user's own traces.</div>\n            <div class=\"english-line\"><strong>Line 8</strong> — Mark bootstrap done. Future calls exit at line 3.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--success\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">⚡</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">The startup hot path</div>\n          <code>deepagents --help</code> and <code>deepagents --version</code> should be near-instant. They trigger zero SDK imports. The Textual app itself only imports heavy packages after the splash screen renders.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 2: Context window management -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Context window management — the \"offload\" trick</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">AI models have a maximum context window — a limit on how many tokens (words, roughly) they can see at once. Long conversations eventually hit that limit. The CLI handles this with a <strong>summarization middleware</strong>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"step-cards\">\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">1</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">Older messages are offloaded</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">When context gets tight, older messages are sent to a separate storage backend (<code>/conversation_history/</code>) and replaced with a compact summary.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">2</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">The AI gets the summary</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">The model sees a short recap instead of the full history, freeing up context space for new work.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card\">\n          <div class=\"step-card__num\">3</div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__title\">Full history is preserved</div>\n            <div class=\"step-card__desc\">The actual conversation is stored in a virtual filesystem. It's retrievable — just not visible to the model unless explicitly fetched.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 3: Unicode security -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Unicode security — hiding malicious commands</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">Some characters look identical but are actually different — an attacker could hide a dangerous command inside what looks like a harmless string. The CLI scans for this.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"pattern-cards\">\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🔍</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Detection</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">The <code>detect_dangerous_unicode()</code> function scans shell commands for homoglyph attacks — characters that look like normal letters but are actually from a different Unicode script.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">⚠️</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Warning</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">If detected, the command is shown with the hidden characters revealed using visual markers (red highlighting on the dangerous codepoints).</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🚫</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Blocking</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Commands with certain dangerous patterns — <code>$(...)</code>, backticks, redirects — are blocked entirely, even if the base command is on the allow-list.</div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 4: Quiz -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Check your understanding</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"quiz\" id=\"quiz-module-5\">\n        <div class=\"quiz__question\">Why does the CLI use a double-checked locking pattern in <code>_ensure_bootstrap()</code>?</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__options\">\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"a\">To make the function run faster</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"b\" data-correct=\"true\">To prevent two threads from running bootstrap simultaneously</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"c\">To make sure the .env file is read twice for reliability</button>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--correct\" data-for=\"b\">Exactly! The first check (outside the lock) lets most calls exit instantly. The second check (inside the lock) prevents two threads from both seeing <code>_bootstrap_done = False</code> and running bootstrap concurrently. This is a standard concurrency pattern.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"a\">The lock actually slows things down slightly. The benefit is safety, not speed.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"c\">Reading .env twice would be a bug, not a feature. The double-check prevents concurrent execution.</div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!-- MODULE 6: When Things Break -->\n<section class=\"module module--warm\" id=\"module-6\">\n  <div class=\"module__inner\">\n\n    <div class=\"module__header animate-in\">\n      <div class=\"module__number\">Module 6</div>\n      <h1 class=\"module__title\">When Things Break</h1>\n      <p class=\"module__subtitle\">Knowing how to debug means knowing where to look. Here's the map.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 1: Debugging -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">The debugging map</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">When something goes wrong, the first question is: <em>where</em> did it happen? Here's where to look for different problem types.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"pattern-cards\">\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🤖</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">AI gives a bad response</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Check the system prompt in <code>agent.py</code>'s <code>get_system_prompt()</code>. Also check the model's <code>AGENTS.md</code> file for conflicting instructions. Try <code>/clear</code> to start a fresh conversation.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">⛔</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Tool call denied</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Check the HITL configuration in <code>_add_interrupt_on()</code> in <code>agent.py</code>. Is the tool listed there? Is <code>auto_approve</code> mode on?</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🐛</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Tool doesn't work</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Check the tool definition in the SDK (not the CLI). The CLI wraps tools from <code>deepagents</code>. Run <code>deepagents -n \"list your tools\"</code> to see what the agent actually has.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🔑</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">API key errors</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Check <code>config.py</code>'s <code>Settings.from_environment()</code>. API keys should come from environment variables. Make sure the right variable is set for your provider.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">🔀</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Slash command not found</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Check <code>command_registry.py</code>'s <code>COMMANDS</code> tuple. Is the command listed there? Also check the <code>bypass_tier</code> — if it's wrong, the command might not be accessible in the current context.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__icon\">📝</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__title\">Memory not working</div>\n          <div class=\"pattern-card__desc\">Check the <code>MemoryMiddleware</code> setup in <code>create_cli_agent()</code>. Make sure <code>AGENTS.md</code> files exist at the expected paths. Run <code>deepagents list</code> to see known agents.</div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 2: LangSmith traces -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">LangSmith — the flight recorder</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">Every agent run is recorded in LangSmith if <code>LANGSMITH_TRACING</code> is enabled. You can replay conversations, see tool calls, measure token usage, and spot where the AI went off-track.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--info\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">🔗</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">The /trace slash command</div>\n          While in the CLI, type <code>/trace</code> to open the current thread's LangSmith trace in your browser. This is the fastest way to inspect what the AI actually did — every tool call, every decision, every token.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--accent mt-6\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">📌</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">The project separation trick</div>\n          The CLI overrides <code>LANGSMITH_PROJECT</code> so agent traces go to a separate project from your own code's traces. This keeps the \"noise\" of your development work separate from the AI's decision trail.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 3: Quiz -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Check your understanding</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"quiz\" id=\"quiz-module-6\">\n        <div class=\"quiz__question\">A user reports: \"The AI keeps ignoring my instructions in AGENTS.md.\" Where do you start debugging?</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__options\">\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"a\">Check if the AGENTS.md file is in the right directory (~/.deepagents/agent-name/)</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"b\">Check if MemoryMiddleware is loading that specific AGENTS.md path</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"c\" data-correct=\"true\">All of the above — and also check if the AGENTS.md content actually contains the instructions in question</button>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--correct\" data-for=\"c\">Right! The full debugging chain is: (1) file exists at the right path, (2) MemoryMiddleware is pointing to it, (3) the content actually says what you think it says. Any one of these failing breaks the chain.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"a\">That's part of it, but there are two other possible failure points — the middleware and the content itself.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"b\">That's part of it too — but don't forget to check the file exists and the content is correct.</div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!-- MODULE 7: The Big Picture -->\n<section class=\"module\" id=\"module-7\">\n  <div class=\"module__inner\">\n\n    <div class=\"module__header animate-in\">\n      <div class=\"module__number\">Module 7</div>\n      <h1 class=\"module__title\">The Big Picture</h1>\n      <p class=\"module__subtitle\">Let's zoom all the way out and see the entire architecture at a glance.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 1: Architecture diagram -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">The full architecture</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"data-flow\" style=\"flex-direction: column; gap: 24px;\">\n        <div style=\"display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap;\">\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-1);\">👤</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">You (terminal)</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div style=\"text-align: center; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 24px;\">↓</div>\n        <div style=\"display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap;\">\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-3);\">🎬</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">main.py</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-3);\">🖥️</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">app.py (Textual TUI)</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-3);\">🔌</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">textual_adapter.py</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div style=\"text-align: center; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 24px;\">↓</div>\n        <div style=\"display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap;\">\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-2);\">🤖</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">agent.py (LangGraph agent)</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div style=\"text-align: center; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 24px;\">↓</div>\n        <div style=\"display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap;\">\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-4);\">⚙️</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Middleware stack</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-4);\">🧠</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Memory</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-4);\">📝</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Skills</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-4);\">🔍</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">MCP tools</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div style=\"text-align: center; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 24px;\">↓</div>\n        <div style=\"display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap;\">\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-5);\">☁️</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Language Model API</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-5);\">🖥️</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Shell / Filesystem</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class=\"flow-actor\">\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-5);\">🌐</div>\n            <div class=\"flow-actor__name\">Web APIs</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 2: Key design decisions -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Why it's built this way</h2>\n      <p class=\"text-lead mb-6\">These aren't accidental — each decision solves a specific problem.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grid-2\">\n        <div class=\"callout callout--accent\" style=\"flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-3);\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">Textual for the TUI</div>\n          <div class=\"callout__content\">Textual was chosen over alternatives (Blessed, npyscreen) because it has first-class async support, reactive state management, and a modern widget model. The learning curve pays off in maintainability.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"callout callout--accent\" style=\"flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-3);\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">LangGraph under the hood</div>\n          <div class=\"callout__content\">The SDK uses LangGraph (from LangChain) to manage the agent's state machine. This handles tool calling, retries, checkpoints, and streaming — things you'd otherwise have to build from scratch.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"callout callout--accent\" style=\"flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-3);\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">CompositeBackend routing</div>\n          <div class=\"callout__content\">Large tool outputs and conversation history are routed to temp directories so they don't pollute the user's working directory. The backend is composable — different paths go to different storage backends.</div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"callout callout--accent\" style=\"flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-3);\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">Skills as files on disk</div>\n          <div class=\"callout__content\">Skills are Markdown files loaded at runtime, not hardcoded instructions. This means non-engineers can add skills by dropping a file in a directory — no code changes needed.</div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Screen 3: Final quiz -->\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen__title\">Final check</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"quiz\" id=\"quiz-module-7\">\n        <div class=\"quiz__question\">You want to add a feature where the AI automatically creates a summary of every conversation when you type <code>/save</code>. Which files would you likely need to touch?</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__options\">\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"a\" data-correct=\"true\">command_registry.py (add the slash command) + agent.py (wire the handler via the summarization middleware)</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"b\">app.py only — it handles all user input</button>\n          <button class=\"quiz__option\" data-answer=\"c\">config.py — that's where all settings live</button>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--correct\" data-for=\"a\">Right! You need to (1) declare the <code>/save</code> command in <code>command_registry.py</code> so it appears in autocomplete and the message queue knows how to route it, and (2) handle it in <code>agent.py</code> — likely by leveraging or extending the existing <code>SummarizationMiddleware</code>.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"b\">app.py handles UI rendering and event routing, but command logic lives in the agent and registry layers.</div>\n        <div class=\"quiz__feedback quiz__feedback--incorrect\" data-for=\"c\">config.py is for settings, not feature logic. You want command_registry.py + agent.py.</div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout callout--success mt-8\">\n        <span class=\"callout__icon\">🎓</span>\n        <div class=\"callout__content\">\n          <div class=\"callout__title\">You've completed the course!</div>\n          You now understand the Deep Agents CLI architecture — the actors, the data flows, the clever patterns, and where to look when things go wrong. You can read the code, understand what happens when you run a command, and make more informed decisions about how to extend it. That's exactly the vocabulary and mental model you need to direct AI coding tools effectively.\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n  </div>\n</section>\n\nHTMLEOF\necho \"Modules 5-7 done\"",
